snippet.textDisplay: I appriciate all the work that went into this, but me being a photographer, I have seen many different variations of photography and phone photography. this is a VERY hard test to due, because every photo (even taken with the same camera) can have different results depending on the lighting and way it was taken in that moment. SO to compare its really not fully accurate on what phone really wins ... then you have the range of people voting on this how many different screen resolutions are different.. I could be looking at these photos on a very high definition screen and then someone else could have a CRAP monitor and vote and not have the same results as the other person.. So there is no TRUE way to vote on this .... the video was a cool idea, but there is no true way of knowing which phone takes the better photo.

snippet.textDisplay:
Weird to decide the better photo is the one everyone didn't pick. Just because it's more accurate and technically complex doesn't mean it's a better look.

There's also probably context to care about. If you're trying to do something or show off something specific, certain filters and effects will matter to guide focus, but just arbitrary pictures with no real context asking which "looks better" is not the same as "which achieves it's goal while still looking good better"

snippet.textDisplay: Bokeh is neither better or worse. It depends on what the photographer desires to be in or out of focus at that moment. Bokeh looks nice, but people generally want know see everything if they're evaluating an image. Watching MKBHD doing a video would feel disappointing if I couldn't see his studio behind him. That's part of the fun.
